WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.600
Good afternoon.

00:00:07.600 --> 00:00:09.620
Welcome to the programming session in the afternoon.

00:00:09.620 --> 00:00:13.840
We're going to jump right in and get started with Gergely, who's going to be talking about

00:00:13.840 --> 00:00:15.360
getting things logged.

00:00:15.360 --> 00:00:17.760
Yeah, thank you very much.

00:00:17.760 --> 00:00:25.719
I'm not sure if the screens are on, but I will start anyway.

00:00:26.240 --> 00:00:31.920
So my name is Gergely Daroczi, and I'm working at SystemOne, which is an ad tech company,

00:00:31.920 --> 00:00:36.720
but I will not talk about marketing, neither about our business models, and neither about

00:00:36.720 --> 00:00:40.119
the statistical models we are using, although there are some interesting problems.

00:00:40.119 --> 00:00:46.320
So we are doing a lot of time series forecasting, hierarchical models with quite large amount

00:00:46.320 --> 00:00:50.880
of data, working with multi-armed bandits and so on.

00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:56.119
But I will just focus on all the open source R packages that we have built mainly to use

00:00:56.119 --> 00:00:57.200
R in production.

00:00:57.200 --> 00:00:59.200
And you can see a couple examples here.

00:00:59.200 --> 00:01:05.040
We have written thin layers around JDBC drivers so that you can easily connect to, let's say,

00:01:05.040 --> 00:01:12.160
to Snowflake from R, and a few other things like being able to use gRPC right from R,

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:15.559
either as a server or as a client, and a few other things.

00:01:15.559 --> 00:01:20.180
And I will focus on this logging for R package.

00:01:20.180 --> 00:01:26.540
But before I focus on this logger package, I would like to clarify what I mean by using

00:01:26.540 --> 00:01:29.660
R in production and what is in production.

00:01:29.660 --> 00:01:31.980
And I included a couple of projects from the past years.

00:01:31.980 --> 00:01:36.820
I will skip many of these and we'll just focus on some important points.

00:01:36.820 --> 00:01:41.199
Like I will not mention the first one that was terrible, but this is happening in a lot

00:01:41.199 --> 00:01:47.459
of companies, I think, writing batch jobs in R that is to be run in an automated way,

00:01:47.459 --> 00:01:52.500
maybe triggered by Jenkins or cron schedule or something like that.

00:01:52.500 --> 00:01:58.699
Maybe just generating reports or doing some ETL processes or doing some daily operations

00:01:58.699 --> 00:02:02.620
like charging fees on customers, card, and so on.

00:02:02.620 --> 00:02:07.940
So this is pretty common, but I think there's no standard way of logging everything in production

00:02:07.940 --> 00:02:10.500
which can be really useful if something goes wrong.

00:02:10.500 --> 00:02:14.380
Also you want to get notified if there's any errors with your jobs.

00:02:14.380 --> 00:02:17.740
I've been using R to be integrated in web applications.

00:02:17.740 --> 00:02:21.660
Jeffrey Horner's R Apache module was great.

00:02:21.660 --> 00:02:26.860
It makes it fairly easy to have scalable APIs written in R, although there are some issues

00:02:26.860 --> 00:02:30.380
like security that you should take seriously.

00:02:30.380 --> 00:02:34.860
Also you need a way of tracking all the errors in a central place and so on.

00:02:34.860 --> 00:02:37.460
And just wanted to mention another thing.

00:02:37.460 --> 00:02:41.660
Using R for stream processing is not a standard thing, I think, but you can definitely do

00:02:41.660 --> 00:02:42.660
that.

00:02:42.940 --> 00:02:47.100
I was working at a fintech company, and we had the debit card transactions coming in

00:02:47.100 --> 00:02:53.820
in real time, and we had some R scripts doing the real-time notifications of our customers

00:02:53.820 --> 00:02:57.059
via text message, email, push notifications, and so on.

00:02:57.059 --> 00:03:00.899
So that's totally doable, but it's not really standard.

00:03:00.899 --> 00:03:04.000
So there are some ways to improve there.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:10.179
So just abstracting this away, I think using R in production is mainly using R without

00:03:10.179 --> 00:03:11.539
manual intervention.

00:03:11.539 --> 00:03:15.820
So having a cron or Jenkins or API request triggered the job.

00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:19.059
Also you should use some containerized environment.

00:03:19.059 --> 00:03:23.300
I would like to emphasize it's not as simple as putting everything in a Docker image and

00:03:23.300 --> 00:03:24.300
you are all set.

00:03:24.300 --> 00:03:29.660
But you have to fix your R version, your R package versions, your operating system versions.

00:03:29.660 --> 00:03:36.059
For example, if you are using Debian testing and the app team decides to do a major version

00:03:36.059 --> 00:03:42.179
update, for example, for the Postgres client overnight, then your jobs might fail.

00:03:42.179 --> 00:03:45.699
Also you have to use a standard R profile and so on.

00:03:45.699 --> 00:03:47.419
I will skip security.

00:03:47.419 --> 00:03:50.660
That's a totally different topic, but really important.

00:03:50.660 --> 00:03:51.940
And I will focus on these.

00:03:51.940 --> 00:03:56.539
So you really have to monitor the jobs to get notified if there's some problem.

00:03:56.539 --> 00:04:01.259
You want to get a notification as a developer, and also you want to notify the users of your

00:04:01.259 --> 00:04:02.619
R applications.

00:04:02.619 --> 00:04:06.699
For example, in our case, the buyers of different campaigns.

00:04:06.699 --> 00:04:11.979
And it's, I think, not enough to monitor the errors, but you have to log everything so

00:04:11.979 --> 00:04:16.380
that if there's a problem, you can debug that pretty easily.

00:04:16.380 --> 00:04:31.339
So some more motivation here, 10 seconds.

00:04:31.579 --> 00:04:36.660
This 10-second video really well describes how I feel about the R code I've written 10

00:04:36.660 --> 00:04:38.940
years ago, or let's say yesterday.

00:04:38.940 --> 00:04:45.739
And I like to use this animation to highlight the importance of version control, but I think

00:04:45.739 --> 00:04:47.940
that's true for logging as well.

00:04:47.940 --> 00:04:52.140
For example, you have this super important business stuff that R script that you would

00:04:52.140 --> 00:04:56.899
like to run, and the only output you get is this one.

00:04:56.899 --> 00:05:01.579
Script out of bounds, I think the most frequently searched term on Stack Overflow.

00:05:01.579 --> 00:05:03.660
And here, at least, you get some hints.

00:05:03.660 --> 00:05:09.779
There's a function called fng, but if you get an error like this one, .subset2error,

00:05:09.779 --> 00:05:14.660
you have no idea what has happened, so logging is important.

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:17.980
I've seen this design in a lot of scripts.

00:05:17.980 --> 00:05:23.820
So you're looping over some vector and printing the iterating variable so that you know where

00:05:23.820 --> 00:05:25.459
the script is happening.

00:05:25.459 --> 00:05:31.339
So that's just a poor man's progress bar, or so that you know where the script failed.

00:05:31.339 --> 00:05:36.299
Or there are some fancier versions of that, logging the timestamp and the percentage left,

00:05:36.299 --> 00:05:37.299
which works great.

00:05:37.299 --> 00:05:42.299
For example, if you have an output like this one, at least you know that the script failed

00:05:42.299 --> 00:05:45.299
after the 17th iteration, but it's not perfect.

00:05:45.299 --> 00:05:50.220
Also, you can log to file by sync or cat, or you can have your own homebrew function

00:05:50.220 --> 00:05:53.940
to do the logging to a log file.

00:05:53.940 --> 00:06:00.700
And this works in most cases, but for example, if you are forking the R process, let me just

00:06:00.700 --> 00:06:02.700
scroll down a little bit.

00:06:02.700 --> 00:06:07.380
Your log lines can be mixed up, and then this subset2error happens.

00:06:07.380 --> 00:06:09.820
You have no idea in which part that happened.

00:06:09.820 --> 00:06:14.100
So I think it's a time to get a proper R package for logging.

00:06:14.100 --> 00:06:15.500
And of course, I did my homework.

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:20.339
I looked around on CRAN, what packages are available for logging, and there are quite

00:06:20.339 --> 00:06:21.339
a few.

00:06:21.339 --> 00:06:25.779
I tried to use this nice regular expression to filter for all the packages related to

00:06:25.779 --> 00:06:28.980
logging, and obviously, I did a very bad job with that.

00:06:28.980 --> 00:06:34.179
Anyway, there are at least 10 packages doing logging on CRAN, but there were some issues.

00:06:34.179 --> 00:06:35.700
I will not get into the details.

00:06:35.700 --> 00:06:41.459
I've written a pretty long apologetics about why I'm not using the other packages.

00:06:41.459 --> 00:06:44.100
If you are interested, please check the GitHub page.

00:06:44.100 --> 00:06:50.179
Anyway, I came up with a design which can be used for all the other R packages.

00:06:50.380 --> 00:06:55.739
This is a design which is flexible enough to fit all the needs of the R users.

00:06:55.739 --> 00:07:00.640
Posted this on Twitter, got some good feedback, so ended up working on this package.

00:07:00.640 --> 00:07:02.100
This is called logger.

00:07:02.100 --> 00:07:04.660
Usage is hopefully fairly straightforward.

00:07:04.660 --> 00:07:10.179
So you load the package, and then you have this log underscore info, warn, error, debug,

00:07:10.179 --> 00:07:13.420
and trace functions, where you can just pass a string.

00:07:13.420 --> 00:07:19.019
So it will just print to the console the log level, the timestamp, and the message

00:07:19.019 --> 00:07:21.059
you have posted there.

00:07:21.059 --> 00:07:22.739
And there are some formatters.

00:07:22.739 --> 00:07:27.380
By default, if the glue package is installed on your computer, that will be used.

00:07:27.380 --> 00:07:30.579
So you can use variable names or R expressions.

00:07:30.579 --> 00:07:33.339
That will be evaluated in your string.

00:07:33.339 --> 00:07:39.140
Glue will do the string interpolation, and here log the number of rows in the data set,

00:07:39.140 --> 00:07:40.820
and so on.

00:07:40.820 --> 00:07:45.420
There are some helper functions in logger, and I will just show you a couple examples.

00:07:45.420 --> 00:07:51.779
For example, this log evil function will evaluate your R expression, this one, and also log

00:07:51.779 --> 00:07:52.779
the result.

00:07:52.779 --> 00:07:54.500
So you can see that this was wrong.

00:07:54.500 --> 00:07:55.500
This is the result.

00:07:55.500 --> 00:08:00.459
This is useful if you just want to record the changing values of a variable in a loop

00:08:00.459 --> 00:08:02.339
or in an R script.

00:08:02.339 --> 00:08:06.799
And this is my favorite one, so log warnings and note the plural form.

00:08:06.799 --> 00:08:12.320
So once you issue this command, from that time, you will get detailed logs about all

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:15.239
the warnings thrown by any R function.

00:08:15.239 --> 00:08:21.720
For example, here, I think this is useful so that now, right away when the warning happened

00:08:21.720 --> 00:08:27.640
with the exact timestamp, not like the default R behavior, printing all the warnings at the

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:29.239
end of the R script.

00:08:29.239 --> 00:08:35.760
A few other things, so logger is mainly to be used in R scripts and not really in interactive

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:36.760
mode.

00:08:36.760 --> 00:08:41.280
So this is a quick example, loading the logger package, listing all the available packages

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:47.320
on CRAN, logging the number of packages available on CRAN, and just iterating over all the letters

00:08:47.320 --> 00:08:52.919
of the English alphabet, counting the number of packages, including that letter, and depending

00:08:52.919 --> 00:08:57.960
on the number of packages, we will either use trace or debug log level to print the

00:08:57.960 --> 00:09:02.200
name of the package with the actual number, sorry, print the actual letter with the number

00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:04.359
of packages related.

00:09:04.359 --> 00:09:05.760
So this is the output.

00:09:05.760 --> 00:09:11.159
You can see that the trace log messages did not show up because by default, we are using

00:09:11.159 --> 00:09:15.919
the debug log level, but I will share more details on that later.

00:09:15.919 --> 00:09:19.119
This was one of the first user requests.

00:09:19.119 --> 00:09:20.919
Can we have colorized outputs?

00:09:20.919 --> 00:09:26.119
Now that's possible if you're interested, although I would like to emphasize that if

00:09:26.119 --> 00:09:31.880
you want to grab outputs, it's probably not the best thing, but that's definitely doable.

00:09:31.880 --> 00:09:37.640
So let me give you a more structured overview on how this logger package works, and I will

00:09:37.640 --> 00:09:43.440
use this example of calling the log info on this string, and in logger, actually, these

00:09:43.440 --> 00:09:45.179
four steps are happening.

00:09:45.179 --> 00:09:48.679
So first, we check if the log threshold is met.

00:09:48.679 --> 00:09:51.039
So this is fairly easy.

00:09:51.039 --> 00:09:56.440
So here we know that the info level is, sorry, the log level is info, and the log threshold

00:09:56.440 --> 00:10:01.200
could be set to, let's say, error, which means I do not want this to be logged.

00:10:01.200 --> 00:10:06.719
So I just exit early, and this is happening fairly quickly, so there's not much overhead.

00:10:06.719 --> 00:10:11.239
On an average laptop like this one, this happens in 20 microseconds, so not speaking about

00:10:11.239 --> 00:10:16.760
milliseconds, it's 20 microseconds, which is important so that you can put as many logging

00:10:16.760 --> 00:10:19.760
functions in your production scripts as you wish.

00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:25.159
If you don't really need the log outputs, you can just set a higher log threshold.

00:10:25.159 --> 00:10:31.520
So next step, after the log level threshold was met, is using the formatter function,

00:10:31.520 --> 00:10:33.280
which is just focusing on this part.

00:10:33.280 --> 00:10:39.099
So the hello curly braces name will be transformed to hello word, because the name was replaced

00:10:39.099 --> 00:10:44.559
by word, so this is just creating the log message that is to be recorded later in the

00:10:44.559 --> 00:10:46.919
means of a log record.

00:10:46.919 --> 00:10:53.960
A log record is a rendered version of the log message, and this simple layout is just

00:10:53.960 --> 00:10:59.520
adding the log level prefix, a timestamp, and the actual message, but you can use other

00:10:59.520 --> 00:11:03.140
layouts like JSON and other things as well.

00:11:03.140 --> 00:11:08.979
The fourth step defines where the log record has to be delivered, which can be a console,

00:11:08.979 --> 00:11:16.580
it can be a file, or it can be a database or maybe Slack, and the end result is here.

00:11:16.580 --> 00:11:22.200
So once you load the package, all these functions are automatically run, so that means that

00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:27.359
Logger is ready to be used right away, no need to set up anything, although you can

00:11:27.359 --> 00:11:31.960
fine tune it to your needs.

00:11:31.960 --> 00:11:36.719
Let me go through all the related atomic items of Logger.

00:11:36.719 --> 00:11:43.039
Log levels are just integers, so making this comparison is cheap.

00:11:43.039 --> 00:11:48.039
We have the log message formatters, for example, the one that I mentioned previously, that

00:11:48.039 --> 00:11:53.400
is using Glue in the background, but you can use Sprintf, maybe because Glue is not

00:11:53.400 --> 00:11:57.640
installed or you just prefer that syntax, and there are a few others, and honestly,

00:11:57.640 --> 00:12:01.599
you can write a log message formatter pretty easily.

00:12:01.599 --> 00:12:07.640
You just have to make sure that you are transforming whatever object is passed to a string.

00:12:07.640 --> 00:12:12.760
Next step is the layout, which is, again, the layout simple is just adding the log level

00:12:12.760 --> 00:12:17.840
prefix, timestamp, and the message, but you can fine tune that to your needs.

00:12:17.840 --> 00:12:24.080
I have this generator function, which provides you quite a few meta variables that you can

00:12:24.080 --> 00:12:26.159
use in your generator.

00:12:26.159 --> 00:12:30.479
For example, it can automatically log the host name, where you are running the R script,

00:12:30.479 --> 00:12:35.960
the process ID, the namespace from which you have been calling this Logger function, and

00:12:35.960 --> 00:12:41.719
so on, and of course, you can have layouts, for example, in JSON and other cases as well.

00:12:41.719 --> 00:12:47.280
The log record destination is one of the most complex things, I think.

00:12:47.280 --> 00:12:53.000
You can log to console file, you can log to both, and you can deliver the messages maybe

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:56.960
to Slack or other instant messaging systems.

00:12:56.960 --> 00:13:03.599
You can send the messages to syslog, you can send the log records to a live stream or to

00:13:03.599 --> 00:13:11.080
a database table and so on, and this is a recent feature, being able to use a log record

00:13:11.080 --> 00:13:17.039
appender in an asynchronous way, and to show you a quick example of that, I'm defining

00:13:17.039 --> 00:13:22.359
my own appender function, which hopefully also demonstrates how easy it is to create

00:13:22.359 --> 00:13:30.119
your own functions, so this is just writing to a given file, but doing that pretty slowly

00:13:30.119 --> 00:13:32.440
after sleeping for a second.

00:13:32.440 --> 00:13:39.719
So once you start using this appender, and you log 25 lines, you can guess what happens

00:13:39.719 --> 00:13:40.719
here.

00:13:40.719 --> 00:13:46.000
This script runs for 25 seconds, not doing anything besides logging, so if you are using

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:51.239
that in a production application, you are blocking your production job by logging, which

00:13:51.239 --> 00:13:53.200
is not cool at all.

00:13:53.200 --> 00:14:00.080
Instead of that, there's an async way of delivering the log record to the destination, and if

00:14:00.080 --> 00:14:04.200
you're interested, it's pretty detailed in the documentation how it's done.

00:14:04.200 --> 00:14:09.679
To keep it short, we have a local message queue where we are just pushing the log records,

00:14:09.679 --> 00:14:16.799
and the actual delivery is done by a background process, which is monitored by your main R

00:14:16.799 --> 00:14:23.760
session, so just to show you a quick example of that, you just need to wrap your appender

00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:30.239
function in appender async, and then it will create your temporary storage for the message

00:14:30.239 --> 00:14:35.719
queue, it will start the background process and monitor it for you for free, and then

00:14:35.719 --> 00:14:40.359
when you run the very same stuff, you will get the results within a few milliseconds

00:14:40.359 --> 00:14:46.479
instead of waiting for the log records actually delivered, and after that, if you are checking

00:14:46.479 --> 00:14:51.679
on the log file, you can see that the background process is still delivering the log records,

00:14:51.679 --> 00:14:57.919
but your R script managed to finish the job in time.

00:14:57.919 --> 00:15:04.280
Last thing about the logger definition, it's not that simple as described here, because

00:15:04.359 --> 00:15:09.479
you can actually have multiple thresholds, multiple formatters and layouts if you would

00:15:09.479 --> 00:15:12.039
like to fine tune that to your needs.

00:15:12.039 --> 00:15:17.320
You do not have to do that, but if you would like to deliver errors to a database, all

00:15:17.320 --> 00:15:23.479
the trace logs to your file and the info messages to your console, that's totally possible.

00:15:23.479 --> 00:15:27.280
Because of time constraints, I will just go through this real quickly, but I will post

00:15:27.280 --> 00:15:35.159
the slides later online, and you will find these examples, so you can just stack all

00:15:35.159 --> 00:15:39.760
these log records pretty easily.

00:15:39.760 --> 00:15:45.960
There are some helper functions, and I will just mention some of these, so there's TikTok

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:53.039
logging, which is just printing the number of seconds since the previous log request.

00:15:53.440 --> 00:15:57.559
Other functions that I already mentioned, for example, the log warnings.

00:15:57.559 --> 00:16:02.080
These guys will automatically capture all the messages, warnings, and errors thrown

00:16:02.080 --> 00:16:11.599
by R and log it properly so that you know when those errors, messages, and so on happened.

00:16:11.599 --> 00:16:17.799
There's a helper function for Shiny, so this is a fairly simple Shiny application, and

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:24.520
this line might not be familiar, so just imputing this single line to your app, it will monitor

00:16:24.520 --> 00:16:30.719
all your inputs, so all these free inputs in your Shiny app, and it will give you free

00:16:30.719 --> 00:16:34.520
logging of all the changes happening in your application.

00:16:34.520 --> 00:16:39.520
So just putting that line in your Shiny app, you will get detailed logs of what inputs

00:16:39.520 --> 00:16:45.359
were changed by the user, which is, I think, really useful to track down how users are

00:16:45.359 --> 00:16:48.960
managing your app and what errors might have happened.

00:16:48.960 --> 00:16:53.559
Using logger in R packages, and this is the main thing why I started to work on logger

00:16:53.559 --> 00:16:59.679
so that it's flexible enough to be used in an R package as the R package developer imagined

00:16:59.679 --> 00:17:05.880
what things should be logged, and giving access to the user to fine-tune where the log messages

00:17:05.880 --> 00:17:07.640
should be logged.

00:17:07.640 --> 00:17:13.719
So a few examples, there's this Boto R package, which is a wrapper around Python's Boto3 module,

00:17:13.719 --> 00:17:17.800
so this is a simple way of interacting with AWS.

00:17:17.800 --> 00:17:23.119
For example, you can read files from S3 by just specifying the object and the function

00:17:23.119 --> 00:17:28.479
to be used, and it will download the file, store it in a temporary file, read everything,

00:17:28.479 --> 00:17:30.319
and clear up your workspace.

00:17:30.319 --> 00:17:31.959
You get some logging for free.

00:17:31.959 --> 00:17:36.479
If you don't like that, you can just kill that, and you can get rid of the log messages,

00:17:36.479 --> 00:17:42.000
or you can actually update the log threshold to be traced so that you get more detailed

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:43.319
logging.

00:17:43.319 --> 00:17:50.040
For example, here it will do the decompressing, it will log the change in the file size, and

00:17:50.040 --> 00:17:53.640
also it will log the cleanup process.

00:17:53.640 --> 00:17:58.359
If you don't like that, again, you can just set, let's say, an error or very high log

00:17:58.359 --> 00:18:03.239
level threshold, and you will get rid of all those messages.

00:18:03.239 --> 00:18:07.119
Another example for logging is this one.

00:18:07.119 --> 00:18:12.920
This is a pretty common pattern in R scripts, using DBI and hard-coding passwords and host

00:18:12.920 --> 00:18:14.520
names in R scripts.

00:18:14.520 --> 00:18:18.560
I didn't like that approach, so I was thinking about something better.

00:18:18.560 --> 00:18:23.959
And just to keep it short, by the way, if you are interested, there are some other related

00:18:23.959 --> 00:18:28.000
slides on my homepage for this.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:31.239
A database connection reference can be as simple as this one.

00:18:31.239 --> 00:18:33.719
For example, just using SQLite.

00:18:33.719 --> 00:18:38.839
For that, you just provide the driver, and let's just use a temporary file for the actual

00:18:38.839 --> 00:18:39.959
database.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:45.520
If you want to run a simple query like this one, select 42, you get logging for free.

00:18:45.520 --> 00:18:50.040
Again, if you want to get rid of that, it's really easy to turn that down, but I think

00:18:50.040 --> 00:18:55.359
it's really important to have this in production jobs, like you see how or when we are making

00:18:55.359 --> 00:18:57.000
the database connection.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:02.839
You get the actual SQL statement logged to your console file, Slack, whatever.

00:19:02.839 --> 00:19:07.280
You get the number of rows, which is important when you are checking production job output

00:19:07.280 --> 00:19:10.199
and you see that no rows were returned and so on.

00:19:10.199 --> 00:19:14.400
And there are some attributes also logged, which might be useful.

00:19:14.400 --> 00:19:22.239
More complex example is using MySQL and just using the Shiny demo server provided by R

00:19:22.239 --> 00:19:23.239
Studio.

00:19:23.239 --> 00:19:26.400
Although the password is not that secret, but still it's not very cool to have this

00:19:26.400 --> 00:19:28.859
in an unencrypted YAML file.

00:19:28.859 --> 00:19:34.640
You can use, let's say, Amazon KMS to do the encryption and decryption for you.

00:19:34.640 --> 00:19:37.959
So using this database connection can be as easy as this one.

00:19:37.959 --> 00:19:44.640
You write your SQL and this package will do the decryption via KMS for you, log the actual

00:19:44.640 --> 00:19:47.400
SQL results and so on.

00:19:47.400 --> 00:19:53.000
Yeah, it's fork safe and there are a few other features that might be interesting.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:57.040
Please check the slides, everything posted on my personal homepage.

00:19:57.040 --> 00:19:58.400
We have some other packages.

00:19:58.400 --> 00:20:03.239
All these packages have, I think, pretty detailed package down documentation.

00:20:03.239 --> 00:20:08.680
If you miss anything, please let me know and I will be happy to improve the documentation.

00:20:08.680 --> 00:20:20.839
And thank you very much and just happy logging to everyone, so thank you.

00:20:20.839 --> 00:20:21.839
Thank you.

00:20:21.839 --> 00:20:22.839
Thank you, Gergely.

00:20:22.839 --> 00:20:23.839
That was a great overview of the logger package.

00:20:23.839 --> 00:20:25.920
We have time for maybe one or two quick questions.

00:20:25.920 --> 00:20:31.319
So you did skip over it right at the end, but how does the logger package log computations

00:20:31.400 --> 00:20:35.640
inside MCL Apply or Parallel LApply?

00:20:35.640 --> 00:20:38.839
Yeah.

00:20:38.839 --> 00:20:40.719
What was the middle part?

00:20:40.719 --> 00:20:47.000
Can I just have a look?

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:54.520
So with MCL Apply, when you are forking, it will actually fork all the appender functions

00:20:54.520 --> 00:20:59.079
and formatter functions or whatever you have defined and will just use those.

00:20:59.079 --> 00:21:06.040
If you are afraid of making that in the case when you are using a database insert as the

00:21:06.040 --> 00:21:09.800
appender, actually the DDBR package is aware of that.

00:21:09.800 --> 00:21:14.880
So when you are forking the process, it can check if the PID changed, and if it did, then

00:21:14.880 --> 00:21:17.239
it will just create a new connection automatically.

00:21:17.239 --> 00:21:21.199
So it's making all these processes pretty fork safe.

00:21:21.199 --> 00:21:23.959
One more quick question.

00:21:23.959 --> 00:21:24.959
Logs are data.

00:21:24.959 --> 00:21:26.800
How do you analyze the logs?

00:21:26.800 --> 00:21:27.800
Yeah.

00:21:27.800 --> 00:21:28.800
That's a great question as well.

00:21:29.520 --> 00:21:32.680
So it really depends on how you define your log message layouts.

00:21:32.680 --> 00:21:33.680
All right.

00:21:33.680 --> 00:21:36.400
It will be pretty difficult to go back to the slides.

00:21:36.400 --> 00:21:41.880
Anyway, you can define the log layout to be, let's say, a JSON line object.

00:21:41.880 --> 00:21:46.560
So this way, you are just logging JSON blobs, and you can just parse that with your favorite

00:21:46.560 --> 00:21:47.560
tool.

00:21:47.560 --> 00:21:54.280
So if you want to analyze your logs, probably you should not use the default text layout,

00:21:55.280 --> 00:21:58.640
You can also deliver the log records to a database.

00:21:58.640 --> 00:22:01.560
So you have that in a structured way right away.

00:22:01.560 --> 00:22:02.560
Okay.

00:22:02.560 --> 00:22:03.560
Thank you very much.

00:22:03.560 --> 00:22:04.560
Thank you.

00:22:04.560 --> 00:22:05.560
Thank you.

